rough such spectacles as public auctions, novel professions like auctioneering, and real estate journalism. As Fitz-Gibbon shows, these innovations sparked impassioned debates on where, when, and how to demarcate the limits of a market society. As a result of these collective efforts, the real estate business became legible to an increasingly attentive public and a lynchpin of modern economic life. Drawing on an eclectic range of sources—from personal archives and estate correspondence to building designs, auction handbills, and newspapers—Marketable Values explores the development of the British property market and the seminal role it played in shaping the relationship we have to property around the world today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aReal property auctionszGreat BritainxHistory. 0aReal property auctions-Great Britain-History. 0aReal propertyzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aReal propertyzGreat BritainxMarketingxHistoryy19th century. 0aReal property-Great Britain-History-19th century. 0aReal property-Great Britain-Marketing-History-19th century. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aBritain.  acommerce.  acultural history.  aproperty market.  areal estate market.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226584478423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226584478/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles